x4freetext: Facility description.
For identifiing light charged particles
MEDLEY set-up
the light charged particles, produced in the reaction
target, were detected by means of eight three-detector
telescopes, each composed of two silicon detectors and
a CsI(Tl)-crystal. The silicon detectors are thin for
the delTa-E1 detectors 50-60 mu-meters and thicker
for the delta-E2 400-500-mu-meters. The material of
E-detectors is CsI(Tl) scintillator crystal, total
thickness 50 mm consisting of a cylindrical and a
conical part. The cylindrical part thickness is 30 mm
and diameter 40 mm which is thick enough to stop
100-MeV protons. Events associated with 96 MeV
neutrons from the beam are selected using a
time-of-flight technique.
A Am-241 alpha-source, introduced in the center of the
MEDLEY chamber, was used to obtain data for the energy
calibration of the delta-E detectors.
.The energy resolution of the complete information
from a telescope is estimated from the overall energy
as derived from the points associated with the
reactions C-12(N,P)B-12-gs  and C-12(N,d)B-11-gs .
A fit of the proton and deuteron peaks from the carbon
target from these reactions, indicate overall
resolutions in the order of 2.2-MeV and 1.8-MeV for
the protons and the deuterons, respectively.
.Two different carbon targets and one polyethylene
C-H2-target were used. The targets, which are disc-
shaped, have the dimensions 0.15-mm thick, 25-mm in
diameter, 0.50-mm thick, 22-mm in diameter and 1-mm
thick, 25-mm in diameter, for the two carbon and one
the polyethylene targets, respectively. The thick
target allows good statistics and the thin one enables
cross checks of the corrections of the energy and
particle losses due to the target thickness.

x4codes.shortRef: Jour: Physical Review, Part C, Nuclear Physics, Vol.63, p.044001 (2001)

x4freetext: - Absolute
cross- sections are obtained by normalisation to the
H(N,P) elastic scattering differential cross-section
at 96 MeV
.Corrections were made for -
- target effect, I.E.Energy and particle losses in the
targets
- collimator effect
- wrap-around effects caused by the interference of
low-energy neutrons, below 22-MeV, with the mono-
energetic neutrons defined by the 96-MeV peak.
- Minor correction of 1%, due to differences in solid
angles between the various telescopes
- TOF-distortion
- Cs-I(Tl) intrinsic efficiency
- dead time.
Calculations with gnash -the two versions of
the gnash code use the exciton model for
pre-equilibrium particle emission and the
Hauser-Feshbach statistical model for equilibrium decay
of the compound nucleus.
The uncertainty in the absolute cross section
normalisation has been estimated to be 4.5%.
Contributions of 2% each from the (N,P)-reference
elastic scattering cross section (see MONIT-REF),
from the target thickness, from the neutron-beam
fluence, from the statistics in the (N,P) elastic
scattering peak, and from neutrons of low-energy
contributing to the (N,P) elastic-scattering peak.
The statistical uncertainties and the systematic ones
including those due to the various corrections are
given in Table 1 and in DATA subents.
